===Etymology 2===
Old English ''swart'', Anglo Saxon ''[[sweart]]'' black; akin to Old Friesian, Old Saxon and Low German ''swart'', Dutch ''[[zwart]]'', German ''[[schwartz]]'', Old High German ''[[swarz]]'', Icelandic ''[[svarir]]'', Swedish ''[[svart]]'', Danish ''[[sort]]'', Gothic ''[[swarts]]''; compare Latin ''[[sordes]]'' dirt, ''[[sordere]]'' to be dirty. Compare [[sordid]], [[surd]]
====Adjective====
# Of a dark hue; moderately black; swarthy; tawny. 
#*'''1590:''' [[w:Edmund Spenser|Edmund Spenser]], ''The Faerie Queene'', Book 2 - A nation strange, with visage swart
#*{{RQ:Shakespeare John}}, III-i - Lame, foolish, crooked, swart, prodigious, 
#*'''1836:''' [[w:Nathaniel Hawthorne|Nathaniel Hawthorne]], ''Old Ticonderoga'' - The merry soldiers footing it with the '''swart''' savage maids

   
2. Gloomy; malignant. [Obs.] Milton. Swart star, the Dog Star; -- so called from its appearing during the hot weather of summer, which makes swart the countenance. [R.] Milton.
Swart (Page: 1456)

Swart, v. t. To make swart or tawny; as, to swart a living part. Sir T. Browne.